snippet.textDisplay: I was diagnosed when I was 34, the specialist said to my face I have it, but that the hospital letter would have to say I have probable EDS as it’s the hyper mobile kind and there is no actual test. snippet.textDisplay: I have been diagnosed with EDS and I suffer acute pain everyday, if it wasn’t for large doses of morphine I really don’t know what I’d do. After finding life too much I asked adult social services for help and now have a carer. I’m in the uk, I don’t know how it works in the states, but I asked for external help as my eldest child was helping me too much personally and helping me look after my three young children which was unfair. Now my carer helps me personally and supports me to care for me younger children freeing my older child to lead her own life. EDS is so very painful, I can sleep for days on end, having a bath will wipe me out completely as it drains all my energy. Don’t underestimate what this poor lady goes through. If I didn’t have children that needed me there are times with the pain I would have killed myself. She doesn’t say it to guilt her daughter, but because life is just too much. She can’t look after herself, I know as I’m there too.

snippet.textDisplay: As someone who has EDS I fear this is going to give us a bad reputation... it’s painful and frustrating but I still go to school, work and swimming has proven to be the best way for me to get moving! My hips pop out of place and pop right back in, my knees ache but I take some ibuprofen and go along with my day. It took me years to get a formal diagnosis. I was around 7 years old when that happened. I remember all the tests that were done to confirm EDS, and the doctor that diagnosed me has since passed but knowing that it’s real and not in my head is such a relief. I have paper work through the university that I’m at stating I have this disease so I’m physically limited but that’s okay I know those limits. I’m almost 20 years old and happy.

snippet.textDisplay: I have 2 parents with chronic health issues.  One is post CVA with physical limitations and needs personal care and assistance.  The other with heart failure, severe COPD. We manage for now.  I have a background providing care to elders.  We need to care for our parents.  Which isn’t always a piece of cake 🍰   I pray for them.   I pray that we all can try to assist.   I’m a caretaker and I need strength to provide and not be critical.  Good days and not so good days.  Your wisdom and insight along with remedial recommendations and/or suggestions.  would be greatly appreciated.

snippet.textDisplay: Sounds like her problems are psychosomatic. A bitter break-up or divorce can really do some heavy duty psychological/emotional damage. It's not in any way an excuse, I think the way she's taking full advantage of her daughter's kindness and love is sickening, but I do hope she gets the help she needs. I've experienced people who stay in a co-dependant/victim state of mind for decades after a bad break-up. It's selfish beyond belief and extremely damaging to those around them because everyone they meet becomes a potential "host" or sympathy giver and towards the people who actually DO give several damns about them, they can become very abusive, hurtful and they begin to believe that your life belongs to THEM.
